{
  "text": "By a contrary, assume that (F 1 , F 2 , F 3 ) admits a reduction of type I or II. Then by the definition (see [CITATION_1] Definition 2 and 3), for some number n \u2208 N\\{0} and some permutation \u03c3 of the set {1, 2, 3} we have deg F \u03c3(1) = 2n and deg F \u03c3(2) = ns, where s \u2265 3 is an odd number. But in the sequence 3, 4, 5 there is only one even number, namely 4. Thus 2n = 4, n = 2 and then ns is, also, an even number, a contradiction. Now assume, by a contrary, that (F 1 , F 2 , F 3 ) admits a reduction of type III or IV. Then by the definition (see [CITATION_2] Definition 4), for some number n \u2208 N\\{0} and some permutation \u03c3 of the set {1, 2, 3} we have deg F \u03c3(1) = 2n and either",
